I'm not an expert in the 40K lore but it seems like I've only seen "abhuman" used in one particular way in the setting. It's a term the Imperium uses for sentient populations whose ancestors were human but who are not human in the sense that they can't interbreed with normal humans. There are isolated populations descended from people who may have been genetically engineered to live under extremely harsh conditions. And there are populations where mutations are very widespread. Ogres are abhumans in the setting, genetically engineered to be hulking slabs of dim-witted and obedient muscle for factory and mining labor on high-gravity worlds, for example, who are often press-ganged and used as shock troops. Because the people writing the material are unimaginative and don't understand biology, or maybe, more cynically, they know what exactly their audience likes to see, mutated "abhumans" have a tendency to have lots of beast features and look really cool and edgy as plastic minis with bat wings or an extra head. "Abhumans" may get rounded up and exterminated and the entire planet glassed, regardless of whether they've actually done anything, if the Imperium decides they're "tainted." Some implementations of SD can't handle more than 75 tags at a time, and every individual word or punctuation mark that it has to parse in the prompt counts as a tag. Sometimes you can break up a longer list of tags by putting "BREAK" in between groups of 75 or fewer tags. Sometimes that'll work, sometimes it won't. Not all implementations of SD work the same way in every detail
